metadata.name: CMYK:Unchecked #33
metadata.description:
CMYK:Unchecked offers almost infinite canvases designed to challenge the concept and state of being unverified.

Layout variations include 80 / 40 / 20 / 10 / 5 / 4 / 1 circles. 
Each circle presented is either Cyan, Magento, Yellow or Black.

---

This work is of course a parody of 'Checks' by Jack Butcher presented in a transformative way. The work is in no way related to the original 'Checks' work and is not intended to fool anyone into thinking so thus does not affect the originals market or value.

metadata.name: Physarum Logo #648
metadata.description:
These past few months have been a great experience and with the beta ending, I wanted to create a piece to thank all collectors and pay tribute to this great platform. 

The piece is based on a physarum simulation with a couple of tweaks, such as continuous behavioural changes and an extra information layer that further manipulates the physarum.

There are ~262k particles simulated in parallel, so it is quite GPU heavy. 

Each piece features one of 12 different colour pallets, the text and a couple of cell-like bodies running around the screen.

Controls: 
S - Save image
H - Hide Text
Click/Touch - Spawn particles

Disclaimer: This is nothing official by the platform itself, merely a tribute by an artist and fan. 

With all that said: Thank you to everyone, and see you in 1.0 !

metadata.name: JAN. 27 #20
metadata.description:
This work is related to the announcement of Genuary 32nd.
The challenge that was stated for January 27 is to create a work in the style of Hilma_af_Klint.
a Swedish artist and mystic whose paintings are considered among the first abstract works known in Western art history.
--------------------
In this work, the goal was to prepare a work suitable for the challenge of January 27, inspired by the work of "The swan" by Hilma , also many of colors are taken from Hilma's works.

metadata.name: Miniscapes #231
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: I AM UNFOLDING #154
metadata.description:
In the past, I was but fragments
Rough and jagged
Indefinitely, I weathered and grew
A sculpture formed, unstructured

In the present, I am the precipice
A grandiose monolith
My angles sharp, my lines precise
A work of art, restructured

The future looms before
A blank formlessness yet to be
My function undefined
In perpetuity, unfolding

-----------------------------------------

Best efforts have been made to optimize this project; however, for best performance, a machine with a dedicated GPU is recommended. Viewing the project in live mode is also recommended.

S - export a high resolution image.
P - pause the animation.

metadata.name: A Gift of Nature #221
metadata.description:
Can nature really be a gift if it isn't ours to give?
Do we feel the need to bind it close in the ways of old to live?
If a gift was given would all be forgiven, a place of harmony now we can live in?

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

A gift of nature, sort of. As natural as a digital gift can be. It is a gen art token of my gratitude you might say. It is the younger sibling of "The Spectrum of Nature". 

This is a gift from me to you, a gift of nature that pulls you through. 

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

To know more about the concept and technicalities of this piece, see the fxtext article “The spectrum of nature - a short making of”. However, feel free to skip the article.

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

Basic info:
The initial render will be 1000px wide and 1000px high. With the ability to scale this up (see below).

The piece uses WebGL, so will perform much better with a graphics card. A faster computer will obviously be better, though I've done my very best to make it fast and efficient for any old laptop. My hope is that you will find the render process quick and enjoyable for the amount of detail that’s present.

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

Controls:
Press the [s] key to save the initial render. You will need to wait a few seconds after all the elements have stopped loading. For the [s] key to work you may need to open in a new tab. But can right click save otherwise.

Larger sizes:
Press the [2-9] keys to save a resolution of that key size. So [2] saves a 2000x2000 size image, [9] saves a 9000x9000 size image etc. Unless you are making some very large prints you probably won’t need more than 4k (even 2-3k is big). Though the option is there.

There may be slight variations in the textures for the larger renders, this is because the shader code has to redraw the textures at the higher pixel resolution, and getting the textures where they sit is more of an art than a science. All the elements remain exact however.

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

Made with javascript and some small extra code:
A palette creator by @nathansonic
Noisejs - github.com/josephg/noisejs - Perlin noise generator
Twgl - github.com/greggman/twgl.js - A small webGL helper.

metadata.name: Countdown #69
metadata.description:
80% of the benefits from primary sales will go to the nonprofit "One Earth", check out their mission and their projects in www.oneearth.org

---------------

We need your help! The Earth is melting!

"Countdown" is a project that tries to show some consequences of global warming and pollution. It does so by representing a glacier that will melt over time, acting as a Countdown for our time left to react to the Climate Crisis.

If you visit this token every other day, the melting will start to be noticeable, and around one year, most of the ice will be gone. The token will also show signs of pollution: the sky colors will desaturate, stars will be less visible on night palettes, and the ice and water will get dirtier. Lastly, the penguin families will start disappearing, as the ice melts and they lose their home.

All the information of the token is available on the browser's console (Features + Token evolution).

---------------
- 365 editions, as the ice will melt almost completely in one year
- 13 color palettes, with different rarities
- 3 ice shades
- Different number of penguin families
---------------

Press "s" to save a 2000x2000px png with the current state of the token

metadata.name: Reaching #39
metadata.description:
Reach for the stars.

However impossible it may seem, there's always a way. As long as you believe.
Everybody has a way to their stars, and the only way to reach it is to try as hard as you can and believe in yourself. I will forever live by this and believe in it.

A couple of the palettes used in this piece were adapted from the ever great Studio Yorktown, thank you for providing these incredible combinations of colors :)

--

Press spacebar or right click to save an image.

--

Reaching is a piece I dedicate to my recently passed grandmother. Rest in piece, we love you and miss you.

metadata.name: Clerestory #181
metadata.description:
Windows welcome daylight, admit fresh air, and offer a view into the outside world. They rarely shatter, always confess the passage of time, and sometimes allow others a chance to look in.

What would the space you're in feel like if it had no windows?

'Clerestory' is an abstract exploration of stained glass windows, drafting shattered sketches for ten potential locations from various perspectives and moments in time. 

Made with WebGL, p5.js, and <3 | CC BY-NC-SA 4.0
